---
import { mobileData, wealthDistributionData } from "../../data/charts";
import BarChart from "../charts/BarChart.astro";
import GiniChart from "../charts/GiniChart.astro";
import HistoryChart from "../charts/HistoryChart.astro";
---

<section id="wealth" aria-labelledby="wealth-heading">
	<div class="section-label reveal-left">Wealth Inequality</div>
	<h2 id="wealth-heading" class="reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.1s">
		The Great<br />Upward<br />Transfer
	</h2>
	<p class="section-intro reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.2s">
		South Africa's inequality is not a post-apartheid failure — it is
		apartheid's success, preserved intact. The 1913 Native Land Act stripped
		Black South Africans of 93% of the country's land. The apartheid state
		built an entire economy on legally enforced cheap labour. When democracy
		came in 1994, the political system changed. The economic system did not.
		In 1996, the ANC adopted GEAR — Growth, Employment and Redistribution —
		an IMF-compatible austerity programme that locked in the structures of
		racial capitalism under a new flag.
	</p>
	<figure class="chart-box reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.1s">
		<figcaption class="chart-title">
			Top 1% Income Share — South Africa, 1914–2025&nbsp;<button
				type="button"
				class="cite-ref"
				aria-label="View source: World Inequality Database"
				aria-controls="cite-popover" aria-expanded="false"
				data-source="World Inequality Database / Chatterjee, Czajka &amp; Gethin"
				data-url="https://wid.world/country/southafrica/"
			>*</button>
		</figcaption>
		<div
			id="history-desktop-chart"
			class="desktop-chart"
			role="img"
			aria-label="Line chart showing top 1% income share in South Africa from 1914 to 2025: around 28% in the colonial era, 24–27% through apartheid, declining to approximately 19–21% after the 1994 democratic transition — but with the 1996 GEAR policy preventing any structural redistribution"
		>
			<HistoryChart />
		</div>
		<div id="history-mobile-chart" class="mobile-chart" role="img" aria-label="Bar chart showing top 1% income share in South Africa at key historical points">
			<BarChart id="history-mobile-bars" items={mobileData.history} />
		</div>
		<table class="sr-only">
			<caption>Top 1% Income Share — South Africa, Key Years</caption>
			<thead><tr><th>Year</th><th>Share</th></tr></thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr><td>1914</td><td>28%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>1948</td><td>27%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>1970</td><td>24%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>1985</td><td>22%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>1994</td><td>20%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2000</td><td>21%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2010</td><td>20%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2018</td><td>19%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2023</td><td>20%</td></tr>
				<tr><td>2025</td><td>20%</td></tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>
	</figure>
	<p class="source">
		Source:
		<a href="https://wid.world/country/southafrica/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">World Inequality Database — South Africa</a>
		(Chatterjee, Czajka &amp; Gethin, 2021)
	</p>
	<div class="two-col wealth-layout">
		<div class="col-text">
			<p>
				Since 1994, the share of wealth held by the bottom half of South
				Africa's population has effectively remained at zero — below 1%.
				Wage suppression, casualisation of labour, and the privatisation
				of public assets have systematically redirected national income
				from workers to capital. South Africa is the world's most unequal
				major economy not despite its democracy but partly because of what
				that democracy chose not to do: redistribute the wealth that
				colonialism and apartheid concentrated. The Freedom Charter
				promised it. GEAR buried it.
			</p>
			<div class="pull-quote reveal">
				<blockquote>
					"The structural legacy of apartheid persists not as an
					accident of history but as the product of deliberate policy
					choices made after 1994 — choices that prioritised investor
					confidence over the redistribution of wealth."
				</blockquote>
				<cite>— Hein Marais, <em>South Africa Pushed to the Limit</em>, 2011</cite>
			</div>
			<p class="source">
				Source:
				<a href="https://wid.world/country/southafrica/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">World Inequality Database — South Africa</a> ·
				<a href="https://www.statssa.gov.za" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Statistics South Africa</a> ·
				<a href="https://www.oxfam.org/en/research/inequality-inc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Oxfam Inequality Report 2025</a>
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="col-charts">
			<figure class="chart-box reveal">
				<figcaption class="chart-title">
					SA Wealth Distribution&nbsp;<button
						type="button"
						class="cite-ref"
						aria-label="View source: WID.world South Africa 2021"
						aria-controls="cite-popover" aria-expanded="false"
						data-source="Chatterjee, Czajka &amp; Gethin, Estimating the Distribution of Household Wealth in South Africa, WID.world, 2021"
						data-url="https://wid.world/country/southafrica/"
					>*</button>
				</figcaption>
				<div role="img" aria-label="Bar chart showing SA wealth distribution: Top 1% owns 55%, Next 9% owns 35%, Next 40% owns 9%, Bottom 50% owns approximately 1%">
					<BarChart id="wealth-distribution-chart" items={wealthDistributionData} outsideValueThreshold={5} />
				</div>
			</figure>
			<figure class="chart-box reveal" style="transition-delay: 0.12s">
				<figcaption class="chart-title">
					Wealth Gini Coefficient by Country
				</figcaption>
				<div
					id="gini-desktop-chart"
					class="desktop-chart"
					role="img"
					aria-label="Wealth Gini coefficients by country (UBS Global Wealth Report, formerly Credit Suisse, 2021): France 0.70, UK 0.71, Germany 0.79, USA 0.85, Sweden 0.88, Brazil 0.89, South Africa 0.89. South Africa shares the highest Gini coefficient of any major economy."
				>
					<GiniChart />
				</div>
				<div id="gini-mobile-chart" class="mobile-chart" role="img" aria-label="Bar chart comparing wealth Gini coefficients across countries, with South Africa at the highest level">
					<BarChart id="gini-mobile-bars" items={mobileData.gini} />
				</div>
				<table class="sr-only">
					<caption>Wealth Gini Coefficient by Country</caption>
					<thead><tr><th>Country</th><th>Gini</th></tr></thead>
					<tbody>
						<tr><td>France</td><td>0.70</td></tr>
						<tr><td>UK</td><td>0.71</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Germany</td><td>0.79</td></tr>
						<tr><td>USA</td><td>0.85</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Sweden</td><td>0.88</td></tr>
						<tr><td>Brazil</td><td>0.89</td></tr>
						<tr><td>South Africa</td><td>0.89</td></tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</figure>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>
